{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e6c8e840-bd10-4a01-9a54-98f6cc682d03","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2** (.NET 9), so you can use the modern constructor-injected `TestContext` and combine sync/async initialization cleanly:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests : IAsyncDisposable\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private HttpClient _client;\n\n    // Sync init + TestContext injection via constructor\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        _client = new HttpClient();\n    }\n\n    // Async per-test init\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        await _client.GetAsync(\"https://example.com/warmup\");\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_testContext);\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_client);\n    }\n\n    // Async cleanup (replaces [TestCleanup])\n    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()\n    {\n        _client.Dispose();\n        await ValueTask.CompletedTask;\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points for MSTest 3.x:**\n\n- **Constructor injection** — `TestContext` is passed via the constructor (no more `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property).\n- **`[TestInitialize]`** — supports `async Task` for async per-test setup.\n- **`IAsyncDisposable` / `IDisposable`** — preferred over `[TestCleanup]` for resource cleanup.\n- **`[ClassInitialize]` / `[ClassCleanup]`** — still available for one-time class-level setup if needed (also support async).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"36e52ed8-bd5a-4368-a36b-edbd7f759ca1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9.0. This is a modern version of MSTest (MSTest v3). Let me provide the recommended modern approach.\n\nIn MSTest v3 (3.x), the recommended patterns are:\n\n1. **TestContext injection**: Use constructor injection instead of the old static property pattern. MSTest 3.x supports constructor-injected `TestContext`.\n\n2. **Initialization**: \n   - Synchronous: Use the constructor or `[TestInitialize]` method\n   - Asynchronous: Use `[TestInitialize]` with `async Task` return type\n   - Class-level: `[ClassInitialize]` and `[ClassCleanup]` both support async\n\n3. **Modern approach (MSTest 3.2+)**: Classes can implement `IAsyncDisposable`/`IDisposable` for cleanup, and use constructor for sync init.\n\nThe cleanest pattern for MSTest 3.x is constructor injection for `TestContext`, `[TestInitialize]` for per-test setup with async support, and `[ClassInitialize]` for class-level setup that also supports async methods.","outputTokens":718,"requestId":"0839:2F47F1:CC5480:EE23A9:69EAC78E"},"id":"4da3b412-cd82-4ce7-b96f-28d1752fd3e8","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:30:04.104Z","parentId":"9f413d59-d59b-4efe-bb9b-7cce93e290a0"}
